# THE GUARD REVISION THIS REPOSITORY AUDITED, BY CONTENT.
#
# release.yml pins the shared release guards by commit SHA. A SHA is
# content-addressed and therefore immutable, so the pin cannot be edited
# under us. What a SHA does NOT do is tell a reader what is in it, and
# what nothing did until this file existed was state which BYTES we
# looked at before pinning them.
#
# Why that gap mattered. The guards prove which revision of themselves
# they run by reading a value the platform hands them and then checking
# that `actions/checkout` fetched that same value. Those two are the
# same number, so the check establishes internal consistency and not
# provenance: hand it the wrong revision and it agrees with itself. The
# question "did the pinned revision run" was answered by a variable
# rather than by anything observable about the files, and when the
# pinned revision and `main` happened to be byte-identical there was
# nothing observable to tell them apart at all.
#
# This file closes that from the CALLER's side, where it can be closed
# without trusting the thing being checked. Every file the guards
# execute is recorded here by SHA-256, taken at the pinned revision.
# tests/test_guard_pins.sh re-fetches each one and refuses any
# difference, so:
#
#   * bumping the pin without re-auditing goes RED, because the digests
#     below describe a revision the workflow no longer names;
#   * a pin that resolves to bytes other than the audited ones goes RED,
#     which is the falsifiable form of "we ran what we pinned";
#   * the check runs offline of any claim the guards make about
#     themselves, before a tag is ever pushed.
#
# WHAT REMAINS TRUSTED, stated plainly rather than papered over: that
# GitHub runs the workflow file living at the pinned SHA. A workflow
# cannot establish its own identity from inside itself, because a
# substituted file could simply print the expected answer. That is the
# platform's guarantee and the reason `uses:@<sha>` is written by SHA.
# Everything downstream of it is checked here by content.
#
# TO RE-AUDIT AFTER A PIN BUMP: read the diff between the old and new
# revisions, then regenerate with
#
#   PIN=<new-sha>; for f in <the paths below>; do
#     gh api "repos/nelsonduarte/capa-language/contents/$f?ref=$PIN" \
#       --jq .content | base64 -d | sha256sum
#   done
#
# and record the new SHA on the `revision` line. Regenerating without
# reading the diff defeats the purpose of the exercise.

revision 2db00705e05b1774cf41eb58006e6533cfca4d55

# AUDIT NOTE, 2db0070, recorded on adoption.
#
# HOW THIS RECORD WAS PRODUCED. capa_authgate already audited this exact
# revision and its guard-pins.sha256 lists the same five files. That
# record was deliberately NOT copied: each digest below was recomputed
# here by re-fetching the file at the pin and hashing it, and all five
# agree with capa_authgate's independently. Copying a digest list is how
# a second copy of a security constant comes to exist without anyone
# having checked it.
#
# WHAT THE PIN CONTAINS. 2db0070 is `fix(ci): job.workflow_sha, and stop
# the guards claiming a proof they cannot have` (#91), and at the time
# of writing it is byte-identical to the compiler repository's main
# (`gh api compare/2db0070...main` reports `identical`, 0 ahead, 0
# behind). Behaviourally, relative to its predecessor 58cf1bf: the
# empty-string context property replaced by the documented one in both
# jobs; the hardcoded guard repository replaced by
# job.workflow_repository, so a fork of the guards no longer silently
# pairs with our scripts; the misnamed "confirm the guards are the
# revision you pinned" step renamed to what it actually checks, that
# actions/checkout honoured its ref; a new optional guard-digests input
# verified by a new script; and GH_TOKEN on the guard 2 step, which is
# what makes `capa install` verify SLSA provenance rather than warn that
# it could not.
#
# ALL FIVE FILES WERE READ AT THIS REVISION, not accepted on their
# digests. Two of them determine what this repository's release will
# actually do and were read closely:
#
#   * tools/capa_floor.sh, because it reads capa.toml's `capa` key to
#     choose which RELEASED compiler the clean room downloads. That is
#     what makes the floor load-bearing rather than documentation, and
#     it is why the floor here moved from >=1.1.0 to >=1.18.1.
#   * tools/clean_room_build.sh, because it executes the
#     consumer-commands this repository supplies. Its fail-closed rules
#     were checked in particular: zero --run commands, an empty --run, a
#     non-absolute room, a non-empty room and a tarball that does not
#     extract to exactly one top-level directory are all errors.
#
# verify_guard_digests.sh IS in this record, because this repository
# passes guard-digests and therefore causes that script to run. An audit
# record that omits a file it causes to execute is not an audit record.

